'''Thornton John Kipper''' (September 27, 1928 - March 29, 2006) was a [[pitcher]] in [[Major League Baseball]] who played from [[1953 in baseball|1953]] through [[1955 in baseball|1955]] for the [[Philadelphia Phillies]]. Listed at 6' 3", 190 lb., Kipper batted and threw [[right-handed]]. He was born in [[Bagley, Wisconsin]]. 

A standout pitcher in college, Kipper spent one year (1946) at the [[University of Wisconsin<U+2013>Madison]] before joining the [[United States Navy|U.S. Navy]] during [[peacetime]]. After being discharged in 1948, he returned to school and played for the UW team from 1949 to 1950. in that last season he posted an 11-1 record, and later went 5-0 in the [[Big Ten Conference]]. He also recorded two victories during the [[1950 College World Series]] and made the All-Star team.

After graduating in 1951, Kipper was signed by the Phillies. In a three-season career, he went 3-4 with 35 [[strikeout]]s and a 5.27 [[earned run average|ERA]] in 55 appearances, including three [[starting pitcher|starts]], one [[save (sport)|save]], and 99.0 [[innings pitched|innings]] of work.

Following his majors career, Kipper pitched in the [[Oakland Athletics|Kansas City Athletics]] minor league system. He also played for the [[Navegantes del Magallanes|Magallanes]] team of the [[Venezuelan Professional Baseball League|Venezuelan Winter League]] (1953-54) and in the [[1954 Caribbean Series]].

After his playing career, Kipper worked in a paper mill in [[Lewiston, Idaho]]. Later served as a [[coach (baseball)|pitching coach]] both at [[Lewis-Clark State College]] and [[Mountain Pointe High School|Phoenix's Mountain Pointe High School]]. 

Kipper died in [[Scottsdale, Arizona]] at age 77. 

